  "text": "Understanding the relative timing of DNA hypermethylation and hypomethylation changes in cancer is crucial to understanding the importance of these changes in various stages of disease initiation and progression. One prevailing model of epigenetic dysregulation in carcinogenesis and disease progression has held that, on average, reduction of DNA cytosine methylation seems to occur early in carcinogenesis in human cancers at the stage of premalignant lesions or even in aging benign tissues and that this hypomethylation precedes and perhaps sets the stage for later gene promoter CpG island hypermethylation changes (reviewed in ref. [CITATION_1] . Some have even hypothesized that age-related decreases in DNA methylation may provide a ''field-effect'' for cancer initiation, perhaps partially explaining the association of most malignancies with advancing age [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
